Marley was surrendered by her owner because she could no longer afford to care for her and she had to move to an apartment. Her owner stated that Marley would sometimes have toileting accidents and that she could not keep her in the apartment if she continued. She also did not want to keep her crated all day either, as that is no life for a dog. Marley is blind and is missing most of her teeth but is in otherwise good health according to the vet. She saw the vet on January 27th, 2021 to get her annual vetting updated. Marley is negative for heartworms and was parasite free from the sample that was collected. She was found to have one small lump near her rear but it was a squishy lump so vet was not concerned that it was anything serious. We completed bloodwork on her as well, due to her age, and everything was normal. Overall, this girl is in good shape and just needs a retirement home where she can spend the rest of her life. Marley enjoys a nice, soft, cozy bed and is a very laid back girl. She gets around quite well even though she cant see. Marley does great with other dogs and has not minded older children. We would not recommend a home with very young children who may try to grab or snatch at her since she cant see and that could startle her. She should do fine with cats as she really doesn't seem to mind anyone and just takes things in stride. Preferably, a quiet, calm home with an older person or couple would he her ideal forever home. Marley is not overly active and does like to cuddle and sleep a lot so a person who enjoys the same would be perfect for her. Please understand that Marley is an older girl so we do not know how long she may have. We are hopeful that she still has several good years left, given her good health, but the reality of adopting an older dog (especially) is that there are no guarantees. Marley's adoption fee will be $175 to help cover her vetting and cost of daily care while with us. If adopted by a senior, Marley qualifies for our senior for seniors program and her adoption fee is only $100. If interested in giving Marley her forever home,please submit your adoption application and interest via email. You may also TEXT ONLY to 352-215-3260(phone calls will not be returned or answered at this number but is your best option for fastest response), FB message us or call 352-493-1255(leave message if no answer) for more info or to set up a day and time to meet her.

Howdy! I'm Spencer. I was found running around on some property one day with a buddy of mine; the folks that lived in the area didn't really like us being there because we chased some chickens ONE TIME! If you ask me, those chickens had it coming. Anyway, one of the families decided that they'd give ARFhouse a call to see if they had space for two more cuties and luckily for us, they did! 

I am the sweetest young Border Collie/Lab mix; approximately 2 years old and I weigh 55 lbs. I have a playful and loving personality; I get along with all dogs and I LOVE humans! I can jump a 6ft. chainlink fence, so I will need a privacy fence at least 6ft. high. I love to run, jump and play with toys; I will make the most wonderful addition to any family. I walk well on a leash, am gentle in nature and I am one of the smartest dogs you'll ever meet. I could use some fine-tuning on my training but I'm sharp as a tack and will pick it up so quickly. 

The fee to adopt Spencer is $200.00; this includes spay/neuter, deworming, vaccinations and a microchip. If you are interested in adopting Spencer, please visit our website. www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. 

**Please Note: Spencer is currently located at our facility in Sherman, Texas. Adoptions are by-appointment only; if you would like to meet Spencer, please fill out an application on our website. Once we have your application, our Adoption Coordinator will follow up with you ASAP with any questions she may have, or to set up a meet-and-greet.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Prince is a wonderful 1-2 year-old Lab/Dobie mix neutered male whose name fits him to a T as he is a perfect gentleman! He came to us from an overcrowded rural county dog shelter so he could take his time finding the perfect new home. While we have no history on Prince, we were impressed with this boy's gentle and kind demeanor from the moment we met him. Prince must have been well cared for at some point in his life as he knows the sit, down, and shake hands commands. He'll eagerly run through his tricks for a yummy treat which he takes very gently. Prince gets along well with other dogs and does enjoy playing chase and wrestling with his fellow foster dogs. He walks quite nicely on a leash for a big guy and will make an excellent walking buddy for his new family. Prince met the resident kitty at the vet clinic with curiosity coupled with shyness so might be fine living with cats in his new home as long as the introductions are done properly. We think that once you meet this great dog you're going to be as smitten with him as we are! Prince weighs about 53 pounds and his adoption fee is $350. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Prince. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Prince and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Kiska is a 2 year old  female Hound Bully mix. She weighs 32 lbs. Kiska is a friendly, spunky and very happy dog. She is engaged with people and wants to be around them. Kiska can jump! She will jump or climb fences if left outside alone. If she is out with people playing she is fine. Adopter will need to stay outside with her, work on training for this and have a run in the meantime so that she is not in danger of getting loose. Kiska was tested with young kids and was gentle - suggest 3 and up. Good with other dogs, good with sharing resources. Positive toy drive and gives up toy gently. Positive food drive and is gentle taking treats. 

She is very friendly and bubbly. While she does have a lot of energy, she will just sit with her person and relax. She loves to play fetch, tug, personal play with her human, and full contact with other dogs. Her playful energy and play style can be a bit much for some dogs. We are working with her on a calm state of mind when she needs to settle. She is a little jumpy so we are also working with her on that. She is getting better at her obedience commands as well. Kiska would benefit from continued training and also would be great at drive sports such as, the wall climb, slat mill, weight pull and spring pole. Those sports would really fulfill her biological needs.

Want to Adopt? 1) Fill out an application on theluckypuppy.org The donation fees are minimum $475 for puppies up to 6 months, minimum $400 for dogs 7 months to 6 years and minimum $ 300 for 7+ years/Special Needs. 2) Once your application is in, our adoption coordinator will contact you and complete a vet check and home visit (possibly electronic). 3) Once approved, please schedule a meet and greet to see the dogs. Meet and greets are by appointment only for approved adopters.

Kiska is available in NY through the Go North Program of The Lucky Puppy Rescue centered in Bonifay and Panama City, FL (NY Lic #1054). This dog is currently in NY. The minimum donation $400 adoption fee includes transportation from FL to NY, spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application/

Laisha (nickname BOBA) is a playful sweet 3 month old puppy with a fantastic temperament. She has terrific potty manners for a young pup and plays very nicely with the resident dog in her foster home. 

She is great with kids as she is in foster with kids and will make a loyal family pet. She needs a family to keep up a consistent routine of regular play and potty trips. 

Laisha would love an active family who will take her on daily walks and outings. She would love to have a home with a yard. 

Laisha will be available after 2/7 as she is awaiting her spay appointment, we will begin screening households that are a good fit as applications come in. 

Please go to our website to submit an application. 
www.anlcf.org

If your household is a good fit a screener will contact you for a video interview and then an in person meeting in San Diego. 

We are not adopting out-of-state at this time.

Follow our rescue on Facebook and/or Instagram. 
https://www.facebook.com/anewliferescue
https://www.instagram.com/anewliferescue/

animal.description:
Apply on our adoption application at leadrescue.org. We do not adopt out of state, only in Illinois and only within 50 miles of downtown Chicago.

Itty Bitty Chihu Committee.

Who else is part of this committee? And who else is part of the “actual” committee from which this saying comes from? ?????Lol it’s nice to get to know new things about people.

Anyways, this itty bitty thing was brought to the shelter because the owner stated they “couldn’t handle one more dog.” Unless this was a house packed with little dogs, how did the smallest of the tribe get the boot? 

Sushi is a 4 year old Chihuahua, completely fun size, rocks a natural fur collar, and does the leave your tongue out while chilling look. He is dog and kid friendly and per typical not yet neutered Chihu-esque fashion, loves to get all up in other dogs’ “business” if they let him. Although he is light as a feather, his drive makes up for his teeny size, his foster said lol. Oh horndogs. Sushi can live in any type of household we believe at this very moment. So far he has shown nothing but all good regular and normal dog things. Still wondering about the original family with too many dogs. Did Sushi father the other dogs?? Are you Montego’s dad??

If interested in going rogue and trying something much more exciting than the amateur California Roll, apply for Sushi at leadrescue.org!

animal.description:
ID #:  A46338395

CJ is a cute dog who's ready for his forever home! Here are a few notes from CJ's behavior assessment:  

Kennel Approach - Excitable response to presence -- jumps up and down, barks. Sometimes growls at strangers but stops when door is opened; easily leashed.
Possession - Shows no interest in toy.
Touch/Handling - Softens with petting, engages tester -- licks, nuzzles, seeks attention, rolls onto back. Lets handler pick him up.
 Food - Eats out of hand, sits for food, lifts head out of bowl, lets handler take bowl.
 Correction - Easily redirects to handler; compliant. 
- rolls onto back; submissive.
 Tested with male Lab mix: interested/social toward other dog. Dogs mounted each other, rolled around on ground with other dog, play bites. 
Overall Behavior - Relaxed, friendly, easy to handle, playful. No signs of kennel stress.

Adoption fee includes vaccinations, spay/neuter, heartworm test, and microchip.
*Dogs are pending behavior and other-animal assessment unless otherwise noted here.

animal.description:
Calla is the sweetest little doll you will ever meet. She was estimated to be about 3 years old, and she weighs just 35 pounds! Calla came to us pregnant and desperate for medical care. She was and IS a fantastic mother and she will be ready to go to her new home in just a couple of weeks. Calla would do best in a home without other dogs. Not because she doesn’t like other dogs, but because she has been through a lot and deserves 100% of someone’s love and attention. She gets upset when her foster dog siblings get loved on because she wants everything to herself and she deserves it! 

Calla also needs a very financially stable family who is able to care for her special needs in case of an emergency. Calla has a rare clotting disorder that makes any surgeries and future injuries very risky. It does not affect callas daily life but in the event that she is ever seriously injured she could bleed too much without the proper medical attention. 

This dog knows she was rescued and she repays her people with lots of love and affection every day. If you want a loyal couch potato companion than calla is your girl. 


If you are interested in adopting Calla please copy and paste our application link into your browser and complete at:

https://daniellethedogrescuer.wufoo.com/forms/zq5l29b022pyq0/

Please no calls or texts. We will process your application and get back to you.

Adopter must be located within a 30 mile radius of Trinity, Florida 34655

animal.description: Coming from a rural area south of San Antonio, the “K Litter” is happy to be here! When they first arrived to SNIPSA, they were bug-eyed, nervous, tails tucked…unsure of their new world. Never having been around humans before, it was understandable. But after a relaxing spa day of warm baths, nail trims, flea and tick removal, and an introduction to big fluffy dog beds, they are LOVING the pet life. The “K Litter” spends their days learning how fun toys can be, snoozing in the sun, and coming out of their shell. It might take a minute for their true personalities to show when you bring one home but after a few days of some patience, love, and routine, the playful and silly puppy personality will shine through! We expect these shepherd mix pups to be medium to large when fully grown. If you’ve been looking for a pup to raise, consider bringing home Kai, Kylo, Kade, or Kyle! Fill out an application at snipsa.org!

animal.description: Opi (9.5yo Female) & Mela (7yo Female) are a bonded mini Dachshund duo. Opi and Mela are retired breeders. They have only recently become beloved pets after their years earning money for their humans. They’re shy and unsure of human affection but they come around after some patience and trust. Both Opi and Mela tend to gravitate to women over men, and couch time snuggles are key to their in home success. Both girls are well mannered in the home and will thrive in an environment with patience; love, and calmness. These girls are petite (hence the mini) so their humans should embrace life with doggie steps to the couch and bed. Opi and Mela are spayed, hw negative, UTD on vaccines, microchipped, and have had dentals. They’re in foster in Broomfield. Adoption fee for the pair is $600. REQUIREMENTS: 1. Fenced yard 2. No kids 3. Calm home with minimal stairs 4. Patient humans willing to continue slow socialization 5. Furniture privileges.  You can apply for Opi and Mela at https://milehighcanine.org/forms-and-applications/mhcr-adoption-application/.

animal.description:
MY NAME IS:  Buddy
POSTED TO PETFINDER DATE:  Jan 29, 2021
SIZE: 76 pounds
APPROXIMATE AGE:   5 years
SHELTER STAFF SAYS:  Buddy loves to run and play. But once you sit down he will be in you're lap giving you kisses and begging for scratches behind his ears. Buddy also love's to play in the mud and make cute muddy paw print's.  He rarely barks, his kennel is never a mess and he knows how to "sit".

Due to Covid, we now work by appointment only and work on a first come basis.  If you are interested in making an appointment, please call the HCHS at 512-793-5463.  You can see all our available animals at HillCountryHumaneSociety.org.
All our adoptable dogs are treated for fleas, given DHPPV and Bordatella vaccines and are de-wormed.  
When you adopt one of our animals it will be micro chipped and registered at the time of adoption.  Also, if not already altered, you will receive a voucher to get your animal spay/neutered.
While we do our best to determine the breeds of our dogs, the majority are strays, and we have only general appearance, coat type, size, ear type, tail, tongue color and coat color to base breed on.  It is always possible when adopting a puppy that it will change dramatically to look like another breed.

animal.description:
Brad Pitt is a very sweet and cuddly 9 month old staffy. He loves people, and is looking for an active home that can spend a lot of time with him. 

Brad has lived with children aged 7 to 13, and did wonderfully with them. He does NOT do well with other animals, so he should be an ONLY pet. 

Brad is house and crate trained. He is a very active and very high energy boy. His new family should be ready to put some work in and get him into training to help him be the best he can be. Brad is a very intelligent dog and will thrive with structure and training. His previous home kept him outside, or crated indoors because he didn't do well with their small dogs. Because of this, he does have some separation anxiety. 

Brad is a gorgeous young dog with a lot of potential. He just needs the right home! Please give then shelter a call if you would like to meet this handsome guy. 520-432-6020

animal.description:
Sophia is a joy to be around! Sophia's original owner chained her up outside, providing her with little comforts of home. Since being rescued she has blossomed into a happy, fun and playful puppy. She is looking for an owner who will continue her amazing progress and work on her basic training. Sophia loves to play and have the freedom of zooming around a back yard with her family at playtime and is so excited to continue her next adventure in life as a house dog. She loves to play and bound around and is hoping for a family who will continue to guide her and show her the rules of the house. Sophia is quite the love, adores her people once she gets to know them, and wants to please and make you happy. Sophia is ready to become the love of your life!
*If you are interested in adopting Sophia please call the shelter (509 662-9577) to set up an appointment to meet her.

Maya is an active, happy, fun loving gal! She loves attention and getting pets, she even enjoyed being brushed today. It seems like the more attention you give her the more she craves. She is looking for a Husky loving home who understands that she will need long daily walks or runs and will need a secure fenced yard or supervised while outside. She is not an apartment dogs and will not be happy cooped up all the time and really enjoys her outdoor adventure time with her people! She seems to know the commands sit and down and thoroughly enjoyed her time on the couch in our enrichment room. She seems to be friendly with other dogs and will do best in a home with no cats or small critters running around. Maya is eager and ready to be a big part of your life!
*If you are interested in adopting Maya please call the shelter (509 662-9577) to set up an appointment to meet her.

animal.description: Coming from a rural area south of San Antonio, the “K Litter” is happy to be here! When they first arrived to SNIPSA, they were bug-eyed, nervous, tails tucked…unsure of their new world. Never having been around humans before, it was understandable. But after a relaxing spa day of warm baths, nail trims, flea and tick removal, and an introduction to big fluffy dog beds, they are LOVING the pet life. The “K Litter” spends their days learning how fun toys can be, snoozing in the sun, and coming out of their shell. It might take a minute for their true personalities to show when you bring one home but after a few days of some patience, love, and routine, the playful and silly puppy personality will shine through! We expect these shepherd mix pups to be medium to large when fully grown. If you’ve been looking for a pup to raise, consider bringing home Kai, Kylo, Kade, or Kyle! Fill out an application at snipsa.org!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Greyson. I am a little 8 week old bundle of boy Chihuahua and possibly terrier. I will probably top out at 20-25 lbs. I have my first shots and am ready to roll.

Puppies require an adopter who is home a good part of the day to continue their training - no exceptions! They are up-to-date on age appropriate vaccines and preventatives and will need to be spayed/neutered at the age of 6 months. Please note, this pup's immune system will not be fully functioning until about 16 weeks of age and therefore, s/he is not suited for Apartment/Condo living or Town homes without a private fenced yard and will not be able to go to public places where s/he could possibly be exposed to the germs of unvaccinated dogs, such as PetSmart/PetCo and dog parks until s/he is 16 weeks old.

The adoption fee for this dog is $375, which helps with the cost of routine vet care. This fee DOES NOT INCLUDE spay/neuter if the pup is not already spayed/neutered. If the animal you are adopting is not already spayed/neutered, you will be required to sign a contract legally obligating you to have the animal altered. ***Note that puppy adoption fees most often help generate revenue that goes towards older, special needs animals that need our help. Surgeries, heartworm treatment, boarding costs....all things that often result in adoptable dogs and cats being left behind to be euthanized. So adopting a puppy saves not just one life, but many! 

For more information, please email kberger@petconnectrescue.org

**If you're viewing this on Petfinder, please visit www.petconnectrescue.org to complete our non-binding application.**

animal.description: HI! My name is Pippa and I am a 7-8 month old border collie mix.  I was born with a condition known as cerebellar hypoplasia (or CH).  It is a genetic condition in which the part of the brain that controls neuromuscular function doesn't develop properly.  As a result, I have a wonky, wobbly walk and have difficulty with fine motor skills.  I also need help getting up; if I happen to fall over on my side i need you to prop me back up.  I have a cool harness that helps me walk and stand and i also have a wheelchair; although I would prefer to walk on my own with just a little assistance from my person.  I enjoy the company of other dogs but I really love people.  My whole face lights up and I actually smile when I see my person.  I love to cuddle and will scoot myself around the house to be near you.  I am good in a crate but would prefer to sleep in a dog bed next to you.  I am up-to-date on my vaccinations and will come with a spay voucher. If you are interested in meeting me, please contact kathie@heridnghaven.org

animal.description:
Midnight is a beautiful senior gal with a frosty face and a warm, loving personality. She's been waiting far too long now for a home of her own, after being turned in with Mercedes, another senior dog, in December of 2019. While we tried for quite some time to get Midnight and Mercedes adopted together, they have shown over the last year that they are not quite as bonded as we initially thought. Midnight is extremely laid-back at 13 years old while Mercedes is a bit more rambunctious, and their personalities sometimes clash. They certainly can be adopted together, but do not have to be. Midnight is such a lady. She's easy going and well behaved. She's housebroken and walks well on a leash, and once she gets to know you, she's your very best snuggly friend. She needs a good diet for seasonal allergies but doesn't ask for much else except a cat-free home. Please give this sweet and sensational senior a chance. File#29429 12/10/19 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org to meet Midnight.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description:
MEET JULIET!!

This is what her Foster Mom says about her..... Juliet is looks to be American Bulldog/Pit Mix/Boxer. Just turned 5 years old. It's long, but worth the read..... she has her own Instagram page at https://instagram.com/juliet_rescue?igshid=a41gj5wt67sc

Hello world, my name is Juliet!

I am looking for my new Mommy/Daddy OR even both! - only ones that will never give me up, I'm over that.

Day/Night house trained - I won't use our home as a potty!

***working on separation anxiety and crate training!

What you should know about me:

Good with men and women

I'll be your best friend!

Everyone who meets me loves me.

I'm skeptical of new people. So I need a min. But once you're my friend it's forever!

I will love you till the end of time and with me you will never be alone ever again!

I CANT BE WITH OTHER DOGS OR CATS - I've had bad experiences before. SO IM AN ONLY CHILD!!!!

even though I can't be with other dogs, on our walk I don't bark at them, and I wag my tail, so no one gets spooked by me.

I attend Mutt Manners on Sunday's (1h) thanks to one love! - I need to keep doing this for maybe a month or 2 more. Foster mom can explain that fun class...

I'm good with children. Haven't been seen with younger than 3, kids too much but open to meeting them. - I'll be cool if they are also! As long as they are polite kids.

I'm cool with every day noises, blender, Kitchen aid at high speed, pressure cooker, washer/dryer, hair dryer (just don't point it at me my hair is fine!).

I have a slight skin allergy - foster mom said fish oil helped more than anything.

When you leave I CAN be out and about, won't destroy our home, just might bark. Working on crate training it's just not my fav place yet.

MY LIKES

PEOPLE! Omg. I love people!

Light walks in the morning & longer walks at night.

I am good with my toys! Sometimes I fetch.

Netflix & Cuddles - oh I'm the best at this.

I like lite playing with my human pals.

Trained to not lay on your bed, but I do like to snuggle with you there!

LOTS OF LOVE

To see you smile and talk to me.

MY DISLIKES:

Other dogo's - THIS IS A MAJOR NO NO. I'm a one woman show. I didn't get much interaction when I was younger, recently got close to a dog and it didn't go too well. - what I lack in I totally make up for!

Being alone for too long.

The idea of going back to the shelter. - I've been passed over far too many times and its left my heart broken. - foster mom, Danielle, is helping me, but I don't think I can survive another broken heart.

Foster Mommy's Notes:

She is a love! My ideal dog!

Came to me knowing basic dog commands. - we are doing refresher courses

I let her chill on the sofa but she didn't go on it without a sheet, so I think this was trained. But when asked to be off she stays off if her bed is there.

Good on walks - working on her slight pulling. Nothing major. She's getting better.

She needs to be introduced to her new home over a few 1-5 day period. I am happy to introduce you to her when you are ready, let you walk her with me, and just get to know her.

I think she needs to go to someone who makes her needs a priority and understands that she is a commitment, loves dogs, and won't give her up for anything.

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please text 480-359-7109 for more information or visit the website for our online application www.underdogaz.com. Juliet is with Freedom Brothers Rescue, but you can use this application.

PLEASE NOTE: This dog is courtesy posted for another individual or Rescue. Different policies and fees may apply.

animal.description:
**I am blind.**

Hi I'm Coco! I am looking for a family who are able to take on my medical needs. I have a rare condition for a young dog and will need regular monitoring, care and attention at home and regular visits to the vet for frequent testing. I may be blind, but I love training and working for yummy hot dog treats and I am learning quickly. I still love to do normal puppy things like running, playing, meeting new people and pups, and of course snuggling.

If you think I might be a good fit for and you are ready to take on my medical challenges, please get in touch with the shelter staff to learn more about me!

If you would like to meet me,  please go to AlexandriaAnimals.org/Adopt-By-Appointment to get more information and to schedule a time to meet with me either via video call or at the shelter. If you have questions about this process, please email info@alexandriaanimals.org or call 703-746-4774, option 2.

animal.description: Coming from a rural area south of San Antonio, the “K Litter” is happy to be here! When they first arrived to SNIPSA, they were bug-eyed, nervous, tails tucked…unsure of their new world. Never having been around humans before, it was understandable. But after a relaxing spa day of warm baths, nail trims, flea and tick removal, and an introduction to big fluffy dog beds, they are LOVING the pet life. The “K Litter” spends their days learning how fun toys can be, snoozing in the sun, and coming out of their shell. It might take a minute for their true personalities to show when you bring one home but after a few days of some patience, love, and routine, the playful and silly puppy personality will shine through! We expect these shepherd mix pups to be medium to large when fully grown. If you’ve been looking for a pup to raise, consider bringing home Kai, Kylo, Kade, or Kyle! Fill out an application at snipsa.org!

animal.description:
~Shiloh is in need of a foster home. His owner is getting ready to move to a place that he can't bring the dog. Shiloh''s a mixed breed. He's about 60 pounds and 7 years old He is up-to-date on shots and neutered.

He is good with people and has lived with other dogs and cats and is good with them also. He's always had a fenced yard so they're not sure how he is without one.

Not sure of his mix but his family thinks could be an Aussie and/or cattle dog mix.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Shiloh is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

animal.description:
Dixie is a 9 years old and 20 lbs of pure love.  She is black with a bit of a silver frost on her muzzle. Dixie loves belly rubs, in fact, she expects her day to start with one.  She likes to hide her treats but living with a beagle, she’s seldom successful in keeping them hid for long.

Dixie was heartworm positive when she came into rescue.  She has successfully gone through treatment and is now a healthy, active dog.  One of the conditions that will be required of her adopter is to commit to keeping dixie on monthly heartworm treatment. She is up to date on all vaccinations and has been spayed.
She is a hearty eater, practically licking the smell off her bowl. She’s a great snuggler, preferring to be on your lap as much as possible.  Dixie gets along with all other dogs she has met. We’re not aware of her experience with cats or small children. 

Our rescue organization only adopts within 3 hour radius from Georgetown, KY.  All our dogs are spayed/neutered and have been fully vetted and current on vaccinations.  Please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and complete an application at:  
https://kentuckydachshundrescue.com/adoption-process--adoption-application.html

BRONSON
When I encountered several javelinas in Amado, I took refuge in a nearby yard. Since I’ve been here at TALGV, I’ve become quite popular, mainly because I’m so friendly, patient and good natured. I know how to sit when told and I can use a doggie door. I may be strong, but I do walk well on a leash. Since I recently demonstrated my climbing ability, I will need an enclosure from which I can’t escape. If you aren’t familiar with my breed, I can tell you that I’m playful, endearing, comical, sometimes stubborn, mischievous, but ALWAYS devoted. I actually thrive on affection and exercise. I’m known as the “ultimate personality breed.” I’m inviting you to be my guest at a “meet and greet” where we can get to know each other. Please accept my invitation!
Arrived: 1-24-2021
1-year-old male Bull Terrier

animal.description:
Karl
Mastiff
Male
5 years old
175 lbs.

**I know I am cute but please read my full bio as I have significant medication costs!

Hey guys, I’m Karl, and I’m going to cut right to the chase here. I’m big. Like really big. So if you’re here looking for one of those little dogs you can fit in a tote bag, you might want to scroll elsewhere on the website.

See, the only bag I’m going to fit into is maybe a sleeping bag if we go camping sometime, but I promise that with my big body also comes a really big heart with a whole lot of love. I am completely happy to spend the day relaxing with my people with maybe a short walk or two. I like to bring my toys to show my foster mom when she comes home, just to know I’ve been thinking about her while she’s away.

I sometimes lean on my people to let them know that I love them and that I’m ready for some affection. I also love to roll in the grass and play with my plushie toys. I’m a pretty stereotypical “gentle giant,” actually. I get along great with other dogs (I live with a couple of chihuahuas in my foster home and they are my best buds!) and I’m just as friendly and easy going as can be. 

I know I sound perfect (and, well….I am!) But here’s the thing. I have some pretty severe allergies and I don’t think anyone has offered me a lot of medical support for them until coming to PawsCo. So I have a lot of catching up to do to get my allergies under control. PawsCo has invested SO much in identifying what my allergies are and the most effective way to get me back to a healthy place. So that’s a great thing! The tough thing is that my medication and special food is all quite pricey (due to the medication itself and also because I’m so big!) For the next 6-12 months, my overall monthly cost will be in the $480-$500/month range. From there, my monthly food/medication cost should drop to $280-$300/month (because I’ll be able to wean off one of the pricier meds at that point.) PawsCo can give you a ton more information but our team asks that you only apply for me if you’re comfortable with supporting long-term medication needs for a pup my size. 

Do you have (a lot) of room in your heart for someone like me? Email my friends at adopt@pawscoadoptions.org and check out this information page: https://pawsco.org/adopt/adoption-process.

animal.description: Hi. My name is Arlo and I am a 2 yr old blue Merle Australian shepherd. MEET TIPPER!  He's a handsome guy with soft fur and Beagle coloring.  His body frame is thin and he weighs around 26 pounds.  He was pulled from a shelter with a broken leg and he was sent to surgery needing pin placement to recover the broken area.  He is currently in rehab and patiently waiting for them to repair the water treadmill to help in his rehab. 
Tipper is crate trained and almost house trained ( he lets you know when he needs to go outside.  He does well on a leash and is up to walking for 20 minutes.  Tipper would do best with older children as he is mouthy to get attention.  Working with a trainer will help curb this habit.  Tipper would benefit from a yard he can run in as he is energetic and active. 
He loves to get on the couch next to you and sack out. Tipper loves to chew on hoofs and a kong. He loves to play and just wants to be with you.  
If you are interested in meeting or adopting Tipper, we have a convenient online application which is the first step.  Click here for application:   https://www.adoptmebluegrasspetrescue.com/.../on-line...
 If you have any additional questions, please contact Adopt Me! Bluegrass Pet Rescue at email: adoptmebpr@aol.com

animal.description:
Linda is a sweet, Sato from the streets of Puerto Rico.  She weighs in at about 34 lbs . The foster mom had this to say about her "She is fine with our three cats and looks to our dog for reassurance and guidance.  She has perfect house manners and is housebroken as far as we have seen.  She walks well on a leash and enjoys exploring our neighborhood.  She does not enjoy the car but maybe as she becomes more confident that could change." Linda might be an adult but she sure does like to chew things like a puppy so will need to be watched for that.   Linda is considered special needs because of an old injury and may or may not need surgery in the future.  We have done Xrays and consulted with an orthopedic vet and she determined that Linda does not currently need surgery but may or may not need surgery in the future. Linda is a very calm dog and not super active so does not appear to be in any pain. If you think Linda would be happy in your home then please fill out an online application today.

Visit the following section of our website if you are interested in adopting Linda:
https://www.capeannanimalaid.org/adopt.html

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Looking to pick up the pace at your house? Ariel, our 10 month-old Feist/All-American Mutt mix is up to the challenge! This adorable and very outgoing pup was at an overcrowded rural county dog shelter before coming to Canine Lifeline to find herself the perfect new home. While we don't have any history on Ariel's pre-shelter life, we have found this girl to be an absolute delight-active, energetic, affectionate, and super playful! She is going to need an active family who can match her energy level and make sure she has plenty of opportunity for exercise, mental stimulation, and training each day. Ariel loves other dogs so would certainly enjoy having a playful canine buddy in her new home. She seems to respond to the sit command when offered a tasty treat (at least most of the time!) and is eager to learn lots more in her new home. Ariel hasn't had much leash work to date as she's all over the place when on a walk. She loves to explore so it's just a matter of daily practice and experience to get her more comfortable on a leash. Ariel has done well with crate-training in her foster home so we expect she should be able to master the house rules quickly in her new home. This girl LOVES toys of all kinds so would enjoy having an overflowing toy box in her new home. Ariel met the resident kitty at the vet clinic and was very curious and attempted to play with her although the kitty wasn't interested in engaging with Ariel. This fabulous young dog is going to make an outstanding companion for the person or family who has the time to spend with an active, energetic, enthusiastic pup. Ariel weighs about 24 pounds and her adoption fee is $375. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. The bandages on her back paws in the photos are from having her dewclaws removed during her spay. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Ariel. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Ariel and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi, my name is Forbes. More information on me coming soon.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $395. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description: Sierra is a two year old Mexican street dog (Potcake). She came to Canada several months ago and unfortunately was not well matched with the family who adopted her. She is a beautiful girl who is shy and uncertain in this new landscape. Unlike most of our canine companions, many dogs like Sierra never lived in a home, experienced the regular day to day goings on of a household or the typical noises and actions that we know as normal. They also aren't used to regular human interactions like the snuggling, walking and playing that we do with our dogs. Almost like a puppy, they need to learn from scratch.  We promise that with the Misfits, Sierra will get the opportunity to relax, unwind and learn about this new world at her own pace. We are confident that Sierra will blossom with slow and steady consideration.

animal.description: Hi there, my name is Royal! I am a fun, sweet, GOOFY boy who loves playing with tennis balls and long naps on the couch. I'm the perfect mix of playful energy and cuddle bug. I spent 2 weeks learning to be a good boy, so I need a family willing to continue to help me remember how. I absolutely LOVE water and would be your best swimming buddy if you let me! I have done well with other large dogs but would do best without cats or small dogs. Because I can be selective with my dog friends, a meet-and-greet with your other dog should happen before you take me home, or I should go to a home as the only dog. Being surrendered at a shelter has been stressful for me, and I'll need someone who can be patient with me and not rush introductions with strangers. If you are willing to give me some time to get to know you, I am a wonderful and loyal companion.

animal.description:
For the love of fluffy butts meet Rico. Rico is a Pomeranian around 10 yrs old we think. He was found in a park. Rico is housetrained, he loves going in and out the doggie door. He does play a little bit if you are on the floor with him. Rico loves car rides and walks. He is fine with other dogs and we assume cats too. He is about 8 lbs. Rico loves food too. He will snuggle with you for a bit but gets a little hot and just wants his bed to lay in. He is too old to be a toy dog for young kids. Rico came in with bad teeth so we gave him a dental. When Rico came to us he seemed fine but then had a couple of seizures, a few were stress related but we are just not sure what is causing the issues. We have done two sets of blood work and x-rays. He is on phenobarbital and a low protein diet that might have to be on the rest of his life.
To help pay for vet bills and care (transportation, food, toys, etc..) a $250 donation is requested at the time of adoption. All of our adoptions are contingent upon an approved application, home visit, reference check, obedience training agreement, and signing of adoption contract. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped before adoption. Our dogs are companion animals that live indoors as part of your family. Please do not apply if your plan is to have them as outside dogs, garage dogs, porch dogs or outside kennel dogs. We do not ship dogs.
All of our dogs are in private foster homes. We are not a shelter with hours. A visit can be arranaged after an adoption questionnaire has been filled out and sent in. Please try email first. We are all volunteers that work so we can not easily take or make phone calls.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Jaxson is a very friendly and outgoing 1-2 year-old Husky/Rottie mix neutered male with one sparkling blue eye and lots of puppy energy. This boy has never met a stranger and seems to make fast friends with all dogs and people that he meets. He found himself homeless at an overcrowded rural county dog shelter and when he wasn't claimed there, made the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could take his time finding the perfect new home. Jaxson will eagerly sit for a treat and may know more commands that we haven't discovered yet. He does need work on taking treats gently though and generally channeling all of that puppy energy in a positive direction. Jaxson LOVES toys of all kinds and was eager to raid the toybox at the end of his photo shoot. He has not had much leash training to date and tends to pull so will need some work in that area. Walking him on a harness as he works on his leash manners will be very helpful. Once he's got some obedience mastered, he's going to make an outstanding running, hiking, or walking buddy. Jaxson did meet the resident kitty at the vet clinic and was very interested and animated with her so likely too exuberant to live peacefully with kitties at this point. He has done well with crate-training in his foster home and may be housetrained too although we can't guarantee it. This big overgrown puppy would love a large yard with an aboveground fence so he could run and play with his new family to his heart's content. Jaxson weighs about 61 pounds and his adoption fee is $350. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Jaxson. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Jaxson and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

True to her name, 11-week-old Felicity is 11 pounds worth of pure bliss. Percolating with puppy pep and personality, she loves snuggling with her foster mom and napping on her lap in between playing with toys and with her doggy foster brother, following him everywhere he goes. Two of her cutest quirks are crawling back and forth under the couch and if her paws get cold outside she jumps on her foster brother's back to warm them up. Never one to turn down treats or food, she's bright as a button and easy to teach, learning "come", "sit" and "stay" and is at work on her leash, crate and housetraining (after all, she IS still a puppy!). Now, with her whole life ahead of her, friendly Felicity will thrive in a loving home, preferably with another playful pup and patient adopters to complete her training, educate her fully and keep her happily active fur-ever.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $395. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

All AAF cats and dogs are vaccinated, spayed or neutered and microchipped. All cats receive a FelV/FIV combination test while dogs over the age of 8 months are tested for heartworms. All pets are also treated for both intestinal parasites and fleas. The AAF is proud of the medical attention that is given to each and every pet as their health and well-being is of the utmost importance to our organization. 
The adoption fee for our pets is as follows:
Kittens: $85
Cats 5 Months and older: $60
Puppies: $150
Dogs 5 Months and older: $135
You can visit this and all of our pets available for adoption:
Tuesday-Friday 4 PM - 7 PM	
Saturday and Sunday 1 PM- 4 PM

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Cookie! Aren't I just so cute? I have a secret - I'm not actually a puppy, I'm just super tiny!! I barely come up to your knees, and I think I'm a lap dog. I'm super sweet and have loved every person I've met so far. I'm super skinny from living on the streets, so I do have a few pounds to gain, but once I'm fattened up I'll weigh less than 48 lbs. (I'd love it if you snuck me a few extra treats until then!) Did I mention I'm also a very good girl who walks well on a leash? Yup, I'm perfect! Adopt me and you won't regret it.
To adopt one of our animals, please visit our shelter, open Tuesday-Friday from Noon-6pm and Saturday from Noon-4pm. You may also submit an application online from our website at http://www.HelpTheAnimalsINC.com/adopt.

animal.description:
Duncan here! I am a Sweet goofy southern boy looking for a home of my very own! The folks here are guessing I have some retriever in my family tree but no one knows for sure! I have been friendly and social with both dogs and people alike! I don't really get how big I am so I would do best in a home with older children! I love to play! I love toys of all sorts, I am sure to be a good snuggler too!


If you are looking for someone to keep you laughing with silly antics, consider meeting me virtually and adopting me today!

Visit the following section of our website if you are interested in adopting :
https://www.capeannanimalaid.org/adopt.html

IMPORTANT:   We strongly recommend checking our website for information on adoption policies and procedures. Please understand that because we are a busy place and because so many animals need our care and attention, adoptions are on a first come basis and no animal will be put on hold. To inquire about a pet's availability or for more information, we encourage you to visit our website. 
Due to the high volume of interest, email and phone inquiries may not be returned on a daily basis. We appreciate your understanding and look forward to your visit! www.capeannanimalaid.org  978-283-6055 ex 10 for reception desk

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

animal.description:
Meet Dagger!  Dagger is a 6-month-old playful Great Pyrenees puppy ready for his forever home.  Dagger is a typical puppy that comes with puppy shenanigans like chewing your favorite chair leg and running away with your shoes, but he wants you to know he's a very good boy and he loves to snuggle and give you lots and lots of puppy kisses.

Dagger is good on a leash and he is doing great at learning basic training, but typical of the breed, he will do them on his time when he's good and ready. All he wants are snacks, toys, a soft sofa to snuggle on, and more snacks.  A good ball for him to fetch would be great, too!

Dagger would do best in an active household with another dog to play with and kids over 6 due to his size.  A fully fenced yard is required as well as Great Pyrenees experience. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ then email Debbie@BigFluffyDogs.com

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
ADOPTION OF A PUPPY UNDER 9 MONTHS OF AGE

The dog you are interested in is a puppy (under a year old). We have criteria for our adoptions of puppies. Puppies are adopted on a foster-to-adopt basis until the puppy is old enough to be neutered/spayed (we prefer them to be no younger than 7 months for females and 9 months for males). Houses with pools must demonstrate that puppies can be protected from the pool with fencing or a cover. Home visits for shots will be required, so puppies are adopted to homes in Maricopa County only. Puppies often have multiple potential adopters, so SPR evaluates what home is best matched with any given puppy and their expected home needs once they have grown.  

Sirus



If you can give Sirus an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organization.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving the life of a puppy and providing for it's FOREVER home.

animal.description:
NOT ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS UNTIL 2/15:
This boy is Bentley....just a young lad between 1 to 2 years old.  He came to us with severe separation anxiety.   He was sent to a dog trainer and put on a mixture of  calming meds to slow the activity in his brain some.  This boy is active and loves the company of other dogs.  Hix separation anxiety is not related to any bad behaviors.  He is very smart and so willing to please.  It is a mental condition just like any mental illness with  people.  You can't train it out of him but you can give him structure, consistency, appropriate exercise and companionship to diminish its affects.   And that is exactly what he is getting in his foster home and he is thriving being the perfect gentleman.  No separation anxiety is being displayed in his current foster.
To adopt Bentley adopters must be willing:
1.  Willing to work with our vet at West Park Animal Hospital to maintain his medications and appropriate doses.  These are drugs that can be called in to any pharmacy.
2.  Live within 30 minutes Elyria/Grafton area for his foster parents and trainer to give appropriate support to new adopter.
3.  Have another doggie companion for him to hang out with and play with.
4.  Have a fenced in yard
5.  Have someone who works from home or only works part time outside of the home so he does not have to be crated 8 hours daily.

**Thank you to Casey who donated towards Goldie's care!**

MY STORY: Goldie came to CBHS as a stray. When Goldie first arrived at the shelter she was very nervous. Since then, Goldie has blossomed into the sweet, loving girl that we know she is. She even loves hanging out in the office to keep us company!

AGE: Approximately 5 years.

TRICKS & COMMANDS: Sit

ABOUT GOLDIE: Goldie is a very people-oriented, sweet, lady. She has a happy, bouncy, personality and would do best in an active home that can help her burn off some energy. 

Goldie enjoys playing with toys, (especially tug of war!), and will sit happily on command for a yummy treat. She loves to show you when she's happy by wagging her tail and giving you an adorable smile with her teeth peeking out!

Goldie has a unique, rambunctious, and "over the top" meeting style with other dogs, which can be overbearing for other dogs, so it would be best for Goldie to meet others in the home prior to adoption.

Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, worming, microchip, and a start on flea/tick prevention.

For more information, please call CBHS adoptions at 319-232-6887 or email at adoptioncounselor@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Dude is a 2 year old very large shepherd. He has not had the best life and we are hoping things change for him. He was neglected by his owner. He spent many hours a day on a short chain in the bed of a pick up truck. He was also allowed to run loose being chased off by people. Living this chaotic lifestyle has made him weary of strangers and other dogs. His owner decided to get a new puppy and bring him to the shelter because he did not get along with the puppy due to his puppy behavior. He has entropy in his left eye and has caused injury to his eye. We are hoping with medical intervention his eye can be saved. He is also high heartworm positive. This boy is much better behaved at the shelter than he was with his owner. He has taken to shelter staff and enjoys meeting strangers and accepting treats. The shelter can tell a big difference in his overall demeanor and the shelter staff would love someone to give this boy a second chance at a happy life. 
He is not available for adoption at this time. He is only available for rescue. Once a rescue has time to assess him and his medical issues he should be available for adoption. 
If you are with a rescue PLEASE contact the shelter directly to learn more about this beautiful boy.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Gabby. I am a little 8 week old bundle of baby girl Chihuahua and possibly terrier. I will probably top out at 20-25 lbs. I have my first shots and am ready to roll.

Puppies require an adopter who is home a good part of the day to continue their training - no exceptions! They are up-to-date on age appropriate vaccines and preventatives and will need to be spayed/neutered at the age of 6 months. Please note, this pup's immune system will not be fully functioning until about 16 weeks of age and therefore, s/he is not suited for Apartment/Condo living or Town homes without a private fenced yard and will not be able to go to public places where s/he could possibly be exposed to the germs of unvaccinated dogs, such as PetSmart/PetCo and dog parks until s/he is 16 weeks old.

The adoption fee for this dog is $375, which helps with the cost of routine vet care. This fee DOES NOT INCLUDE spay/neuter if the pup is not already spayed/neutered. If the animal you are adopting is not already spayed/neutered, you will be required to sign a contract legally obligating you to have the animal altered. ***Note that puppy adoption fees most often help generate revenue that goes towards older, special needs animals that need our help. Surgeries, heartworm treatment, boarding costs....all things that often result in adoptable dogs and cats being left behind to be euthanized. So adopting a puppy saves not just one life, but many! 

For more information, please email kberger@petconnectrescue.org

**If you're viewing this on Petfinder, please visit www.petconnectrescue.org to complete our non-binding application.**

animal.description:
Wyatt - approximately 8-9 years old, 43 lbs, neutered male, probably a Husky/Chow or Husky/Aussie mix.  

Wyatt was a stray who came into one of the animal control facilities that we regularly work with and he soon won the hearts of all the Animal Control Officers.  Wyatt is indeed a lover, but he’s also very unsure of what it means to live in a house and to have people treating him with kindness, love, and respect.  

When Wyatt first came to the foster home, he was extremely unsettled.  He clearly did not understand what he was supposed to do or how he was supposed to react to household activities.  If he was crated or tethered, he was calm and looked like he felt safe.  If he could wander free, he would wander non-stop, clearly restless and lost.  Once restricted again, he would sigh and settle right down.  After several weeks, the restlessness finally started to subside, although it is not totally gone.  If his foster Mom is in motion, then Wyatt is right beside, behind or in front of her.  After about 5 months in foster care, Wyatt has become more approving of himself, prouder of himself, more confident, with much better focus.  

Wyatt is essentially a plush, loveable teddy bear of a dog; however, he has two major issues.  Despite every effort, he cannot be fully housetrained.  He will appropriately pee and poop outside, but he retains a marking habit indoors.  Wyatt has been trained to wear a male diaper when indoors, and that, coupled with a degree of restriction can reduce or eliminate the marking behavior.  

The second issue is Wyatt’s almost single-minded focus on food.  He will counter surf, stove surf, and even try to grab food on your plate or in your hand.  He has tried to climb into the dishwasher to get at dirty dishes.  He will eat anything food-related, even a container that had food in it.  Wyatt’s foster mom has to be careful about dropping food on the floor or doling out treats to the whole pack of dogs.

Wyatt also has easy, uncomplicated, and straightforward traits.  He responds well to grooming and handling.  He rides well in a car and is eager to jump in and go.  Wyatt is crate trained.  He stays in a closed crate when his foster Mom leaves the house and he sleeps in a closed crate at night in the foster Mom’s bedroom.  He follows his foster Mom from room to room but will usually settle in a designated spot and go to sleep.  He gets along quite well with the other dogs in the house, as well as with the three cats, although he clearly did not have much socialization with dogs in his earlier life.  Wyatt walks well on a leash with a “no-pull” harness.   

Wyatt is a younger senior dog.  He has some cataract development, not unusual for his age.  He also has significant hearing loss, although he responds to certain sounds if within about 10 feet.  He will respond to “kissy” sounds, loud handclaps, and a handbell.  Wyatt is otherwise a healthy boy.  

Careful management is the key to living happily with Wyatt.  He will need to wear a belly band/male diaper when indoors to preserve his adopter’s sanity.  We have also determined that he will be most comfortable in a home with at least one other easy-going dog.  He clearly takes comfort from his foster dog pack and he did not do well in another foster home without a canine companion.  

Wyatt would do best with a person or people who have a calmer lifestyle and a peaceful home.  Wyatt would not do well in a home with children due to his obsessiveness over food.  Wyatt’s adopter should also be willing to make regular use of crating and tethering for the dog’s comfort.

If you are someone who is looking for the unconditional love that only a dog can provide but is willing to live with canine imperfection; someone with patience and the ability to empathize while a new dog finds himself in his new environment; someone who wants to adopt an older dog and just love him to pieces until the end then Wyatt might just be your perfect match!

If you are interested in any of our rescues, please fill out our non-binding application which can be found here - www.hedgesvillehounds.com (or https://hedgesvillehounds.wixsite.com/home).  You will need to copy and paste the URL into your browser.  You may also contact us using the "Contact this Organization" button above.

animal.description:
Humane Society/SPCA of Nelson County - ALMOST HOME

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

Phone: 434 263-7722
Email: pets@nelsonspca.org

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

GOOD NATURED, SWEET GIRLUPDATE 1/29/21: (Written by Sigrid)
Sweet Melissa is a Hound (mix) who is about 18 months old and weighs 51 pounds. When she was vetted and spayed on 1/26/21 she tested NEGATIVE times 4 on her 4DX test-this is always GREAT news. She has such a good nature and was even sweet during her vet appointment.
Melissa is the definition of hound-ready to go, full of play, a strong voice when needed, good-natured, and most of all lovable.
Her sleek tri-colored coat begs you to touch it, and if you do, she will reward you with giddy happiness. This type of coat is an easy keeper-a few sweeps with a soft bristle brush and occasional bath will keep her looking perfect.
Melissa is an athletic dog that is looking for fun and direction. At only 18 months old and 51 pounds, she is just moving out of being a pup and ready to learn all the lessons to become a great home companion. She loves attention and treats, and toys make her really pay attention. (A treat motivated dog is often a dog who learns things quickly because they love being rewarded with delicious things.) So far, she thinks all people are wonderful and when I introduced her to our cats, she thought they were interesting, but she was respectful toward them.
This healthy girl needs active folks willing to put a little time in to teach her what she should know. Exercise is important so an enclosed yard where she can run, play games, and fetch balls is ideal.
If you think you would like to include a sweet hound in your life and experience their legendary kind of love and devotion, Melissa is waiting.
NOTE: All animals are spayed/neutered as soon as practical after arriving at our facility unless there is a medical issue that may cause a delay or they are too young to be spayed/neutered. VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org
